{{technical|date=March 2015}}
'''Dunathan stereoelectronic hypothesis''' is a concept in [[chemistry]] to explain the stereospecefic cleavage of bonds using [[pyridoxal phosphate]]. This occurs because [[stereoelectronic]] effects controls the actions of the [[enzyme]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Silverman|first1=Richard B.|title=The organic chemistry of enzyme-catalyzed reactions|date=2002|publisher=Acad. Press|location=San Diego, Calif. [u.a.]|isbn=9780126437317|edition=Rev.}}</ref>
==History== Before the correlation between fold type and reaction correlation of [[proteins]] were understood, Harmon C. Dunathan, a [[chemist]] at [[Haverford College]]<ref>http://www.haverford.edu/chem/mackay/ColinWeb/MacKay_Web.html</ref> proposed that the bond that is cleaved using [[pyridoxal]] is perpendicular to the system.<ref>http://chemgroups.ucdavis.edu/~toney/Stereoelectronic.html</ref> Though an important concept in [[bioorganic chemistry]], it is now known that enzyme conformations play a critical role in the final chemical reaction.
==Mode of action== The [[transition state]] is stabilized by the extended [[pi bond]] network (formation of [[anion]]).<ref>http://chem.uaf.edu/keller/Courses/654Fa11/PDF/654-10-6-11.pdf</ref> Furthermore [[hyperconjugation]] caused by the extended network draws electrons from the bond to be cleaved, thus weakening the [[chemical bond]] and making it [[labile]]<ref>http://chemgroups.ucdavis.edu/~toney/Publications/BBA%20-%20Proteins%20and%20Proteomics%202011%20Toney.pdf</ref> The [[sigma bond]] that is parallel to the [[pi bond]] network will break.<ref>http://faculty.washington.edu/gelb/Chp9.ppt</ref> The bond that has the highest chance of being cleaved is one with the largest [[HOMO-LUMO]] overlap.<ref>{{cite book|last1=editors|first1=Mohammed Shahid ... [et al.],|title=Biomedical aspects of histamine current perspectives|date=2011|publisher=Springer|location=Dordrecht|isbn=9789048193493}}</ref> This effect might be effected by [[electrostatic]] effects within the enzyme.<ref>http://www.chem.wisc.edu/areas/organic/studsemin/steinkruger/steinkruger-sem.pdf</ref>
==Applications== This was seen in [[transferase]] and future interests lie in [[decarboxylation]] in various [[catalytic cycles]].<ref>http://www.life.illinois.edu/biochem/455/Lab%20exercises/5GOT/PLP%20enzyme%20review.pdf</ref>
