The '''Kadam virus''' (or KAD, strain MP6640) is a [[tick]]-borne [[Flavivirus]].<ref name=archive>{{cite web|title=Kadam virus MP6640|url=http://www.european-virus-archive.com/Portal/produit.php?ref=110&id_rubrique=1|publisher=www.european-virus-archive.com|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>

==Located==
The virus was first isolated by the [[Uganda Virus Research Institute]] in [[Entebbe]], [[Uganda]] after samples were taken from cattle in Karamoja in 1967.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Henderson BE, Tukei PM, McCrae AW, Ssenkubuge Y, Mugo WN |title=Virus isolations from Ixodid ticks in Uganda. II. Kadam virus—a new member of arbovirus group B isolated from ''Rhipicephalus pravus'' Dontiz |journal=East Afr Med J |volume=47 |issue=5 |pages=273–6 |year=1970 |pmid=5473597 |issn=0012-835X |url=https://www.cabdirect.org/cabdirect/abstract/19721000702}}</ref> The viruses were usually only found from [[Rhipicephalus]] and [[Amblyomma]] ticks around Kenya and Uganda infecting cattle and humans.<ref name=Wood82>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wood OL, Moussa MI, Hoogstraal H, Büttiker W |title=Kadam virus (Togaviridae, Flavivirus) infecting camel-parasitizing ''Hyalomma dromedarii'' ticks (Acari: Ixodidae) in Saudi Arabia |journal=J. Med. Entomol. |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=207–8 |year=1982 |pmid=7086856 |doi=10.1093/jmedent/19.2.207 |url=https://academic.oup.com/jme/article-abstract/19/2/207/2219961/Kadam-Virus-Togaviridae-Flavivirus-Infecting-Camel}}</ref>

==Spread==
Around the beginning of the 1980s the Kadam virus was found to be spread in Saudi Arabia by [[Hyalomma]] ticks<ref name=Wood82/>  when found on a dead camel at Wadi Thamamah in [[Riyadh]].

