{{cleanup|reason=links should be formatted as External links or reference notes|date=May 2013}} '''Magneto-inertial fusion''' (MIF) describes a class of [[Nuclear fusion|fusion]] devices which combine aspects of [[magnetic confinement fusion]] and [[inertial confinement fusion]] in an attempt to lower the cost of fusion devices.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.gaianxaos.com/pdf/physics/magnetized_target_fusion.pdf|title=Why Magnetized Target Fusion Offers a Low-Cost Development Path For Fusion Energy}}</ref> MIF uses magnetic fields to confine an initial warm, low-density [[plasma (physics)|plasma]], then compresses that [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]] to fusion conditions using an impulsive driver or "liner."
Magneto-inertial fusion approaches differ in the degree of magnetic organization present in the initial target, as well as the nature and speed of the imploding liner. Laser, solid,<ref>{{citation|url=http://fusionenergy.lanl.gov/Documents/FRX-L-MachinePaper-RSI-July2003.pdf|title=FRX-L: A Field-Reversed Configuration Plasma Injector For Magnetized Target Fusion}}</ref> liquid and plasma<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.icarusinterstellar.org/plasmajet-driven-magnetoinertial-fusion-pjmif/|title=Plasma-Jet Driven Magneto-Inertial Fusion}}</ref> liners have all been proposed.
Magneto-inertial fusion begins with a warm dense plasma target containing a [[magnetic field]]. Plasma's [[electrical conductivity|conductivity]] prevents it from crossing magnetic field lines. As a result, compressing the target amplifies the magnetic field.<ref>{{citation|url=http://iopscience.iop.org/1742-6596/112/4/042084/pdf/1742-6596_112_4_042084.pdf|title=Status of the US program in magneto-inertial fusion}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=F. J.|last1=Wessel|first2=F. S.|last2=Felber|first3=N. C.|last3=Wild|first4=H. U.|last4=Rahman|title=Generation of high magnetic fields using a gas‐puff Z pinch|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1059071|journal=Applied Physics Letters|date=1986-04-28|issn=0003-6951|pages=1119–1121|volume=48|issue=17|doi=10.1063/1.96616|first5=A.|last5=Fisher|first6=E.|last6=Ruden|bibcode=1986ApPhL..48.1119W}}</ref> <ref>H. U. Rahman, F. J. Wessel, and N. Rostoker, Staged Z-pinch. Physical Review Letters 74 (1995), 714.</ref> Since the magnetic field reduces particle transport, the field insulates the target from the liner.
== In popular fiction == The starships in Mike Kupari's novel ''Her Brother's Keeper'' are propelled in part by magneto-inertial fusion rockets.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Kupari |first=Mike |year=2015 |title=Her Brother's Keeper |location=Riverdale, New York |publisher=Baen Books |page=40 |isbn=978-1-4767-8090-0 |oclc=920469663 |url=http://www.baenebooks.com/p-2848-her-brothers-keeper.aspx}}</ref>
